{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16293"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16293"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.08,0.56,0.16,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8984"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"8563"},{"type":"tags","id":"10300"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21378"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sense of smell relies on a sophisticated neural network that transmits information from nasal receptors to various regions of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the olfactory pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary olfactory neurons project directly to the temporal lobe","Olfactory information is processed exclusively in the olfactory bulb","Secondary neurons project via the olfactory tract to multiple brain regions including temporal lobe","Olfactory receptor neurons synapse first in the amygdala","Each odour molecule activates only one specific receptor type"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory system follows a specific sequence where \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary neurons project via the olfactory tract to multiple brain regions including temporal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E. The pathway begins with olfactory receptor neurons in the nasal cavity that form connections within the olfactory bulb with mitral and tufted cells. These second-order neurons then send their axons through the olfactory tract to reach several destinations including piriform cortex, amygdala, and entorhinal areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary olfactory neurons project directly to the temporal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E - these neurons must synapse in the olfactory bulb before reaching cortical areas. \u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory information is processed exclusively in the olfactory bulb\u003C/strong\u003E - smell processing involves multiple brain regions beyond the bulb. \u003Cstrong\u003EOlfactory receptor neurons synapse first in the amygdala\u003C/strong\u003E - initial synapses occur within the olfactory bulb, not the amygdala. \u003Cstrong\u003EEach odour molecule activates only one specific receptor type\u003C/strong\u003E - odour molecules typically activate multiple receptor types, enabling the detection of numerous distinct smells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Olfactory signals travel from primary neurons in the nasal epithelium to the olfactory bulb, then through the olfactory tract to reach multiple regions including temporal cortex.","The processing of smell involves sophisticated neural circuits with multiple connections and concurrent pathways.","Due to bilateral inputs and network redundancy, damage to one side of the olfactory system may not cause noticeable deficits."],"references":["Yoo HB, Umbach G, Lega B. Neurons in the human medial temporal lobe track multiple temporal contexts during episodic memory processing. Neuroimage. 2021 Dec 15;245:118689. doi: 10.1016/j.neuroimage.2021.118689. Epub 2021 Nov 3. Erratum in: Neuroimage. 2022 Aug 15;257:119281. doi: 10.1016/j.neuroimage.2022.119281. PMID: 34742943; PMCID: PMC8802214.","Catani M. The connectional anatomy of the temporal lobe. Handb Clin Neurol. 2022;187:3-16. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-12-823493-8.00001-8. PMID: 35964979.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T17:19:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T17:19:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8984"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":nu